Execution Model Analysis

The interpreter uses a recursive depth-first evaluation with memoization (`executed` Set). This is simple but has fundamental limitations:

```typescript
// nex-runtime.ts:118-128 — Recursive evalNode
private async evalNode(node: NexNode): Promise<Record<string, any>> {
  if (this.executed.has(node.id)) {
    return this.results.get(node.id)!;  // Memoization
  }
  // ... execute ...
  this.executed.add(node.id);
  // Follow sync/depend links
  for (const link of outgoing) {
    if (link.type === "sync" || link.type === "depend") {
      await this.evalNode(nextNode);  // Recursive descent
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

Problems:
1. Stack overflow risk on deep graphs (>10,000 nodes) due to recursive execution
2. No execution timeout at the interpreter level (only in `ProductionNexInterpreter` wrapper)
3. Memory leak: `results` Map grows unbounded; no eviction policy
4. No cancellation: Once started, a graph execution cannot be interrupted
5. Race conditions: Parallel branches share the same `results` Map with no synchronization primitives

Agent Orchestration & Self-Modification

The `agent` node kind is a stub — it returns a metadata object but does not actually spawn any computational entity:

```typescript
// nex-runtime.ts:208-218 — Agent execution is purely descriptive
private async executeAgent(node: NexNode): Promise<Record<string, any>> {
  const data = typeof node.data === "string" ? JSON.parse(node.data) : node.data;
  return {
    type: "agent",
    id: node.id,
    role: data.role,
    goal: data.goal,
    instructions: data.instructions,
    spawned: true,  // False claim — nothing is spawned
  };
}
```

The `MultiAgentDispatcher` (`multi-agent-dispatcher.ts`) provides actual concurrency but each agent is just a separate `NexInterpreter` instance — there is no shared state, no message passing, and no agent lifecycle management beyond "pending/running/completed/failed".

Self-modification via `rewrite` nodes is equally descriptive:

```typescript
// nex-runtime.ts:188-197 — Rewrite returns pattern/replacement but never applies it
private async executeRewrite(node: NexNode): Promise<Record<string, any>> {
  return {
    type: "rewrite",
    id: node.id,
    pattern: data.pattern,
    replacement: data.replacement,
    applied: true,  // False claim — graph is not modified
  };
}
```

Verdict: The architecture is conceptually sound but implementationally hollow. The primitives exist as types and documentation, but their runtime behavior is shallow. This is acceptable for a v0.1 prototype but dangerous for a v2.5.0 claim.

