2.3 Performance & Scalability

Runtime Efficiency

The interpreter is single-threaded, single-process with no worker threads or clustering. For the claimed "1000+ concurrent agents", this is physically impossible on one Node.js/Bun event loop.

Benchmarks from test suite:
- 1000 simple executions: 30s threshold (30ms each) — extremely slow for empty graphs
- 100-node sequential graph: 5s threshold — 50ms per node is unacceptable
- 50 parallel branches: no threshold specified

Root causes of slowness:
1. `NexInterpreter` is reinstantiated for every execution (no reusable VM)
2. Graph validation runs on every instantiation (O(n) link validation)
3. No JIT compilation or bytecode generation — JSON is interpreted recursively
4. `Map` lookups for every node resolution (should use array indexing)

Distributed Execution

The `DistributedExecutor` (`distributed-executor.ts`) has a sound theoretical design:
- Graph partitioning via connected components (DFS)
- Topological scheduling with phase-based execution
- Replication strategy (configurable factor/consistency)
- Cluster node registration with health tracking

But it is entirely local:

```typescript
// distributed-executor.ts:280-290 — "In production, send to remote machine"
private async executePartition(...) {
  // Create a sub-graph from partition
  const subGraph: NexGraph = { ... };
  // Execute locally (in production, send to remote machine)
  const interpreter = new NexInterpreter(subGraph);
  const result = await interpreter.execute();
}
```

There is no RPC, no message queue, no network layer for distributed execution. The `NexHttpClient` exists but is only used for external API calls in tool nodes, not for inter-node communication.

Concurrency Model

`MultiAgentDispatcher` uses a naive concurrency limit:

```typescript
// multi-agent-dispatcher.ts:45-55
if (this.runningCount < this.concurrencyLimit) {
  await this.executeAgent(agent);  // Awaits completion!
} else {
  this.queue.push(agent);  // Unbounded queue — memory leak risk
}
```

This is not true concurrency — it sequentially executes agents up to a limit. A proper implementation would use `Promise.all()` with a semaphore or worker pool.

Resource Management:
- No memory limits per agent
- No CPU throttling
- No I/O quotas
- No garbage collection tuning

