2.5 Reliability & Robustness

Error Handling

The system uses three incompatible error strategies:
1. Throw and crash: `nex-runtime.ts` throws on guard denial, invalid links, unknown node kinds
2. Return error objects: `ProductionNexInterpreter.executeWithSafety()` catches and returns `{ error: string }`
3. Silent failure: `StorageAdapter` stubs return `null` or `true` without throwing

This inconsistency makes it impossible for callers to handle errors reliably.

State Management & Persistence

All storage is in-memory or stubbed:

```typescript
// storage-adapter.ts:45-55
public async connect(): Promise<void> {
  switch (this.config.type) {
    case "sqlite": await this.initSqlite(); break;  // Stub
    case "postgresql": await this.initPostgres(); break;  // Stub
    case "mongodb": await this.initMongoDB(); break;  // Stub
    case "memory": break;  // Only working backend
  }
}
```

```typescript
// storage-adapter.ts:280-290
private async initSqlite(): Promise<void> {
  console.log("[Storage] Initializing SQLite...");
  // In production, use sqlite3 or better-sqlite3
}
```

There is no actual persistence. Graphs, execution records, and user data vanish on process restart. The `memoryStore` is a `Map` with no eviction, no TTL, and no backup.

Guard Conflict Resolution

The `GuardConflictResolver` (`guard-resolver.ts`) implements a precedence-based resolution:

```
Precedence: deny > escalate > rewrite > spawn-critic > allow
```

This is deterministic and safe (deny-first is correct). However:
- It only handles 4 conflict types; real-world guards may have arbitrary combinations
- No truth-density tie-breaking beyond simple numeric comparison
- No temporal ordering (older guards vs newer guards)
- No guard composition (AND/OR of conditions)

Merge Strategies

Five strategies exist (consensus, vote, synthesize, first-success, last-result) but:
- `consensus` just checks `results.length > 0` — no actual agreement detection
- `vote` always returns `results[0]` — no voting logic
- `synthesize` returns a string summary — no semantic merging

```typescript
// nex-runtime.ts:228-248
private mergeConsensus(results: Record<string, any>[]): Record<string, any> {
  return { consensus: results, agreed: results.length > 0 };  // Trivial
}
```

Self-Bootstrap Validation

The `AgentRewriter` tracks which modules are "agent-written" vs "human-written" but:
- No actual code generation or application
- No validation that generated code compiles
- No rollback mechanism
- No diff/patch management

